The paper deals with counting problems in graph theory, which is a central topic in computational complexity theory. The use of Kneser graphs and the study of special graph classes suggest a focus on combinatorial and geometric aspects of the problem, which are typical of subfields such as computational complexity (cs.CC), discrete mathematics (cs.DM), and graph theory (cs.DS). The mention of Ladner's theorem and the adaptation of proofs to $\mathsf{W[1]}$ also point to a strong emphasis on parameterized complexity theory, which is covered by subfields such as computational complexity (cs.CC), graph theory (cs.DS), and theoretical computer science (cs.TH). Finally, the title of the paper suggests a broad scope and a universal relevance of the results, which could fit under subfields such as computational geometry (cs.CG) and game theory (cs.GT).
